</ul>

<p>You‚Äôve got a powerhouse CPU, a monstrous graphics card, plenty of supercharged RAM and more storage than you know what to do with.</p>

<p>Now it‚Äôs time to house those components in a bad ass case ‚Äî otherwise, they‚Äôll be no good.</p>

<p>Okay, you could probably build a wall mounted PC without a case, but that‚Äôs another story.</p>

<p>We‚Äôre taking a look at the best PC cases for the money in 2020 (hey, that rhymes!)</p>

<p>Let‚Äôs dive in:</p>

<h2 id="how-do-i-choose-a-pc-case">How do I Choose a PC Case?</h2>

<p>Here‚Äôs what you need to consider when choosing a PC gaming case:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Size</li>
  <li>Form Factor</li>
  <li>Cooling Support</li>
  <li>Hard Drive Bays</li>
  <li>Airflow</li>
  <li>Cable Management</li>
  <li>Sound Proofing</li>
  <li>Modularity</li>
  <li>Aesthetics</li>
  <li>Budget</li>
</ul>

<p>With that in mind, let‚Äôs talk about each one in a bit more detail:</p>

<h3 id="size--form-factor">Size &amp; Form Factor</h3>
<figure>
<img class="lazyload" alt="different size cases diagram" data-src="/img/cases/different-case-sizes.png" />
<figcaption><p>Source: <a href="https://www.computercaselab.com/">Computer Case Lab</a></p></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>First up, we have the size and form factor of your case. These go hand in hand, which is why we‚Äôre discussing them both at the same time.</p>

<p>Your case‚Äôs form factor has a tremendous impact on the components you can use in your build.</p>

<p>The three main case form factors are ATX, Micro ATX, and Mini ITX, but those names primarily refer to the type of motherboard it can house.</p>

<p>ATX motherboards are the largest of the three, followed by Micro ATX and Mini ITX, respectively.</p>

<p>ATX cases are generally larger, while Mini ITX cases tend to be a bit smaller, but that‚Äôs not always the case.</p>

<p>For example, some cases are smaller in physical dimension but can still house a full-size ATX case. Check out our guide on the <a href="/budget-pcs/smallest-atx-cases/">smallest ATX cases</a> for more examples.</p>

<p>The size of your case will also have a big effect on the other components you can include, such as your graphics card, CPU cooler, hard drives, optical drives, case fans, etc.</p>

<figure>
<img class="lazyload" alt="cool case" data-src="/img/cases/cool-case.jpg" />
<figcaption><p>Source: <a href="https://www.gamersnexus.com/">Gamers Nexus</a></p></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>For example, if you want to overclock your CPU like a boss, you‚Äôre gonna need a water cooling unit and a bunch of fans ‚Äî or at the very least, a pretty beefy air cooler.</p>

<p>And if your case is too small, it may not accommodate a water cooling radiator or enough fans to get the job done.</p>

<p>Another example is hard drive storage space.</p>

<p>If you want a ton of hot swappable hard drives in your PC, or an optical drive, you‚Äôll need to make sure the case is big enough to fit them.</p>

<div class="quick-tip">
  <h4>Quick Tip<i class="box-icon-spacing fas fa-check"></i></h4>

  <p>Hot swapping hard drives is incredibly convenient, whether you're building a NAS or a regular gaming PC.</p>

  <p>We have a full guide on <a href="/pc-cases/hot-swappable/">hot swappable PC cases</a> that you can check out by clicking that link. </p>

  <p>Now back to the guide!</p>

</div>

<p>A lot of case manufacturers are removing optical drive bays (5.25‚Äù) from their cases altogether as physical discs become more obsolete.</p>

<p>That being said, there may be some instances where you‚Äôd need an optical drive, and a water cooler, and 8 drives. If that‚Äôs the case, you‚Äôll need a large, spacious case with enough room to accommodate your components.</p>

<p>And that‚Äôs not even taking cable management into account, which we‚Äôll get to further down the page.</p>

<p>Lastly, your case needs to be big enough for your GPU ‚Äî the last thing you want is a GPU that won‚Äôt fit in your case.</p>

<p>After ordering the parts for my first gaming PC, I was beyond hyped to put the thing together and smash 1080p ultra settings. Unfortunately, my components had other plans.</p>

<p>Everything was assembled but the GPU, the last part of my building process. But to my dismay, it was an inch too long and wouldn‚Äôt fit in my case without getting caught on the hard drive bays, which couldn‚Äôt be removed.</p>

<p>Luckily, sites like <a href="https://www.pcpartpicker.com/">PC Part Picker</a> will show you the maximum supported GPU length of any case on the market. I recommend leaving at least a few inches of breathing room, just to be safe.</p>

<p>Smaller cases also tend to be harder to work with, since there‚Äôs less wiggle room to work with. If you‚Äôre a new builder, sticking to a standard, mid-tower ATX case is a good idea.</p>

<p>However, the decision is yours ‚Äî it‚Äôs your PC, and you can do whatever you want with it.</p>

<h3 id="cooling-support--included-fans">Cooling Support &amp; Included Fans</h3>

<figure>
<img class="lazyload" alt="airflow-diagram" data-src="/img/cases/airflow-diagram.jpg" />
<figcaption><p>Source: <a href="https://www.evga.com/">EVGA</a></p></figcaption>
</figure>

<p><strong>TLDR: Some cases come with a bunch of fans pre-installed, and others come with jack squat. Also, many cases have the option to add your own fans, of varying sizes. Check the case‚Äôs fan configuration before buying to make sure your parts receive optimal airflow and remain cool during intense use.</strong></p>

<p>As we touched on above, you should consider your case‚Äôs cooling support before buying.</p>

<p>Plan on water cooling?</p>

<p>Make sure your case can fit an adequately sized water cooler and radiator fan. Most premium cases will support 120mm and 240mm radiators, but not all of them.</p>

<p>Radiator support aside, you also need to think about how many fans you can mount inside the case.</p>

<p>I have 3 fans in my PC build: two intake fans, and an exhaust fan. There‚Äôs a lot of debate online about the optimal cooling setup.</p>

<p>The answer?</p>

<p>It depends. If you‚Äôre not doing anything crazy with your PC like running 8 hard drives, four graphics cards, and an overclocked CPU, having a few fans in almost any configuration will be fine.</p>

<figure>
<img class="lazyload" alt="case fans" data-src="/img/cases/case-fans.jpeg" />
<figcaption><p>Source: <a href="https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/">Computer Case Lab</a></p></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Especially if you leave the stock fans in your case (assuming it‚Äôs a good case) you‚Äôll be fine. But you can always add more case fans if your case supports it.</p>

<p>For example, many cases will come with a certain number of fans included, with the option of adding 3-5 more yourself.</p>

<p>While we‚Äôre on that note, let‚Äôs discuss included fans.</p>

<p>Some cases come with more fans than you‚Äôll know what to do with, while others don‚Äôt come with any fans at all. If you‚Äôre not comfortable with configuring fans properly, it‚Äôs best to buy a case with them pre-installed for you. It‚Äôll make your life way easier.</p>

<h3 id="hard-drive-bays">Hard Drive Bays</h3>
<p><img class="lazyload" alt="hard drive bays" data-src="/img/cases/hard-drive-bays.jpg" /></p>

<p>Adding storage to your PC is (obviously) essential if you, oh I don‚Äôt know, plan on using your PC.</p>

<p>I don‚Äôt want to discuss mechanical hard drives versus solid state drives or NVME drives ‚Äî that‚Äôs a separate discussion for a separate article.</p>

<p>What you need to know now, however, is your case has a maximum number of supported drives.</p>

<p>In addition, there are three different types of drive bays:</p>

<ul>
  <li>5.25‚Äù</li>
  <li>3.25‚Äù</li>
  <li>2.5‚Äù</li>
</ul>

<p>5.25‚Äù drive bays are primarily used for optical drives, and are becoming less common as the years pass.</p>

<p>3.25‚Äù bays are standard for mechanical hard drives, and pretty much every case on the market will come with (at least) a few of them.</p>

<p>2.5‚Äù drive bays are primarily used for solid state drives, but a lot of SSDs come with adapters that allow you to install your SSD in a 3.5‚Äù drive bay.</p>

<p>If you want a ton of storage, opt for a case with more drive bays, but know there may be less space for other components as a result.</p>

<div class="quick-tip">
  <h4>Quick Tip<i class="box-icon-spacing fas fa-check"></i></h4>

  <p>Some cases have more storage than others. If you're interested in building a traditional gaming PC, you probably won't need a crazy amount of storage.</p>

  <p>On the other hand, building a NAS system is going to require a special case with plenty of storage support.</p>

  <p>We've created a list of the <a href="/pc-cases/nas/">best NAS cases</a> on the market for your NAS PC build. Click the link to check it out!</p>

</div>

<h3 id="airflow">Airflow</h3>
<figure>
<img class="lazyload" alt="case airflow diagram" data-src="/img/cases/case-airflow.png" />
<figcaption><p>Source: <a href="https://www.howtogeek.com/">How to Geek</a></p></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Your case‚Äôs airflow is another big one ‚Äî most cases nowadays have decent airflow, but you should still read the reviews beforehand to double check.</p>

<p>Make sure you have positive airflow (more air is coming in than going out) to ensure your components stay nice and cool.</p>

<p>There are several ways to configure your case‚Äôs airflow, but that‚Äôs a topic for another post.</p>

<p>For a full guide on airflow, click <a href="https://www.howtogeek.com/303078/how-to-manage-your-pcs-fans-for-optimal-airflow-and-cooling/" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>

<h3 id="cable-management">Cable Management</h3>
<figure>
<img src="/img/cable-management/good-cable-management.png" alt="example of good cable management" />
<figcaption><p>Source: <a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/pcmasterrace/comments/4erbjx/just_built_a_pc_for_my_friend_pretty_good_cable">Mocha_Bean on Reddit</a></p></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Despite popular belief, your case‚Äôs cable management actually doesn‚Äôt have a huge impact on airflow.</p>

<p>That‚Äôs not to say you should forget about cable management altogether ‚Äî obviously a well cable managed rig is going to have better cooling than a jumbled mess. That means a healthier environment for your components, and a longer lasting PC overall.</p>

<p>Cable management is more important from an aesthetic standpoint. Considering most cases on the market have a side-panel window, it‚Äôd be a shame if your rig looked like a jumbled turd because you didn‚Äôt properly manage your cables.</p>

<p>Different cases have varying levels of cable management solutions. My first case didn‚Äôt have much room behind the back panel for cables, so I ended up having to stuff them all inside my case.</p>

<p>Even with my semi-modular power supply, it didn‚Äôt look pretty. In addition, there weren‚Äôt many grommets for cables in the right places, so routing my cables was a pain in the ass.</p>

<p>Next time I buy a case (and this is my advice for you too) I‚Äôd read up on the case‚Äôs cable management options.</p>

<p>You should consider how much space is behind the panel, how easy it is to manage cables, and where your grommets are located.</p>

<p>For more information on <a href="/cable-management/">cable management and whether or not it matters</a>, click that link to check out our full guide.</p>

<p>We also have a page about the <a href="/pc-cases/cable-management/">best cases for cable management</a> if you want to check that out as well.</p>

<h3 id="sound-proofing">Sound Proofing</h3>
<figure>
<img class="lazyload" alt="sound-proofing" data-src="/img/cases/sound-proof-mod.jpg" />
<figcaption><p>Source: <a href="https://www.linustechtips.com/">Linus Tech Tips</a></p></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Some cases are louder than others, and to be fair, this is largely dependent on the fans. Companies like Be Quiet! Are made to operate silently, whereas other companies don‚Äôt seem to give a damn about how loud their fans are.</p>

<p>For starters, buy fans that aren‚Äôt too loud. You can read reviews about the case fans noise levels, and many manufacturers will disclose how loud the case fans are by dB. However, it‚Äôs hard to trust their numbers, since they‚Äôre incentivized to lower them.</p>

<p>If you‚Äôre hellbent on choosing a case but its stock fans are loud, you can always buy new, quiet fans and replace the stock fans.</p>

<p>You also want to consider how sound proof the case is. Some crappy cases don‚Äôt contain sound well at all, while others are designed purposely with sound proof materials.</p>

<h3 id="modularity">Modularity</h3>
<figure>
<img class="lazyload" alt="modular case" data-src="/img/cases/modular-case.jpg" />
<figcaption><p>Source: <a href="https://www.pinterest.com/">Pinterest</a></p></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>As mentioned previously, many cases are doing away with 5.25‚Äù drive bays altogether to make room for other components.</p>

<p>This way, small ATX and Micro ATX cases can still fit large graphics cards.</p>

<p>Luckily, many higher end cases are modular, meaning you can install or uninstall certain components as you please.</p>

<p>Want to add an optical drive? No problem. Want to add a tri-fan GPU that‚Äôll bump into your drive bays? No problem, just remove it.</p>

<p>Modularity isn‚Äôt a necessity, but it‚Äôs certainly a nice luxury to have as it helps to futureproof your build. (Although, according to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moore%27s_law" target="_blank">Moore‚Äôs Law</a>, is it even possible to future proof?)</p>
<h3 id="aesthetics">Aesthetics</h3>
<p>This one doesn‚Äôt have much to do with the functionality of your case, but if you‚Äôre like most enthusiasts, you want your case to look badass.</p>

<p>RGB lighting and sick designs won‚Äôt impact performance, but it‚Äôll definitely make you feel a lot cooler.</p>

<p>After all, you‚Äôre investing a lot of time and money into your build, so you might as well be proud to see it sitting atop your desk in all its glory.</p>

<p>Cases come in all different shapes, sizes, colors, etc. I personally like minimalistic designs with some nice lights and a tempered glass side panel window, but this one‚Äôs totally up to you.</p>

<h3 id="budget">Budget</h3>

<p>Lastly, we have a budget.
To be completely honest, there‚Äôs no sense in spending more than $100 for a budget build, and you can usually get away with the sub $60 price point.</p>

<p>However, enthusiast builders who are investing a large chunk of change into their builds will probably want the best case they can get their hands on, which can run north of $150-$200, or more in some cases (no pun intended.)</p>

<p>Don‚Äôt spend a ridiculous amount of money on your case, but don‚Äôt skimp out on it either. I‚Äôll typically spend 5-10% of my budget on the case, depending on the grade of the build.</p>

<h2 id="are-pc-cases-important">Are PC Cases Important?</h2>

<p>Cases aren‚Äôt going to have a tremendous impact on your performance ‚Äî spending $300 on your case isn‚Äôt necessarily going to help you crush 1440p Ultra settings, for example. But it will have an impact on your cooling performance, and which components you can house, which do impact performance. Not to mention the aesthetics of your build.</p>

<p>In short, PC cases have a bigger impact on the looks of your build than its performance, but that doesn‚Äôt mean you should overlook your case.</p>

<h2 id="is-a-bigger-pc-case-better">Is a Bigger PC Case Better?</h2>

<p>If you‚Äôre planning on hauling your PC case around for LAN parties, a bigger case is obviously a bad idea. But if you want to house multiple GPUs in your case, or you‚Äôre planning on having a dual chamber PC setup, a bigger case is definitely better.</p>

<p>Again, it really depends on your needs. Larger cases tend to be more expensive, as do smaller cases. Mid tower cases are the most common and therefore, the most reasonably priced (on average).</p>

<p>However, if you don‚Äôt want a big and bulky monstrosity sitting on your desk, you can opt for a <a href="/budget-pcs/smallest-atx-cases/">small ATX case</a> or even a super <a href="/budget-pcs/smallest-micro-atx-cases/">small Micro ATX case</a>.</p>

<h2 id="are-bigger-fans-better">Are Bigger Fans Better?</h2>

<p>Bigger fans can push more air at a time, even when spinning at a lower RPM. I‚Äôd say in general, bigger fans are usually better, but that‚Äôs not to say you can‚Äôt get by with a standard 120mm fan.</p>

<h2 id="why-are-pc-cases-so-big">Why Are PC Cases so Big?</h2>

<p>First of all, not all cases are big, but large cases are designed to house more components. Some enthusiasts like to use multiple GPUs in an SLI or Crossfire configuration, use 8+ hard drives and install massive cooling rigs. You need a big case with enough room to house everything. Bigger cases also boost your ego a bit too, but that‚Äôs another story.</p>

<h2 id="how-many-pc-fans-do-you-need">How Many PC Fans Do You Need?</h2>

<p>The answer to this question depends on how hot your PC will be, which is determined by the components you‚Äôre using. AMD is known to run hotter than Intel, but this will also be affected by whether or not you‚Äôre overclocking, how many drives you have, how many GPUs, etc.</p>

<p>In addition, you should consider cable management, the power of your fans, how well your case distributes airflow, the size of your fans, etc.</p>

<p>Generally you can‚Äôt go wrong with 3-5 fans, depending on their size and how hot your PC will be.</p>

<p>You can test the internal temperature of your PC with computer software and a thermometer, and adjust the amount of fans and their speed to achieve an optimal temperature of 40-45 degrees celsius ambient.</p>

<h2 id="are-pc-cases-universal">Are PC Cases Universal?</h2>

<p>Generally speaking, a case that supports a large ATX motherboard will also support Micro ATX and Mini ITX, but that‚Äôs not always the case (again, no pun intended‚Ä¶)</p>

<p>Double check the case‚Äôs specifications before buying to make sure your motherboard is compatible.</p>

<h2 id="should-i-get-a-mid-or-full-tower-case">Should I Get a Mid or Full Tower Case?</h2>

<p>Most people will be fine with a standard ATX mid-tower case. I‚Äôve used one my entire life without any issues, nor have I felt the need to upgrade.</p>

<p>Enthusiast builders that want to stuff their rig with a million high-end components and water coolers might need a full tower case to house everything, but that‚Äôs about it.</p>

<p>From a functionalist perspective, full tower cases are only necessary if you have a ton of crap to put inside. Otherwise, it‚Äôs more of a looks type of deal. Totally up to you.</p>

